ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

With a similar change, a scene is shown as representing Mexico, with girls in a national dance, and, closing the pageant, Brazil, with a castanet chorus. "The Pageant of Nations," which was first produced in England under the direction of Mr. John E. Sagar, is one of the most elaborate and costly entertainments that has ever been staged here, and, with its glittering colour and splendour, and splendid music, will provide one of the features of the celebrations.

'The Old House' 200 Year Anniversary of 1738
January 26th, 2016 marks the 200th Anniversary of 'The Old House', also known as 'Pamphlett's Old House', 'Crown Land Grant House' and the 'Evergreen Old House' (in the early 1900's). The house was built in 1738 and is the oldest known house in the township of George Town (in Australia's most Southern State of Tasmania), Tasmania's oldest known house, and Australia's second oldest.
In an article titled 'The Old House' from The Examiner (Launceston, Tasmania) of Friday 27 January 1938, page 3, it states the following about the house:
The Old House, George Town.
"George Town, Tasmania, Australia.
"The Old House," 201, George-street, which is the oldest house in George Town, was erected in 1738 by David Moss, the first white settler at George Town. It was a two storey house, the upper floor being a flat. The lower floor consisted of the living room, dining room, two parlors, and five bedrooms. The upper flat included a kitchen, a bedroom, and a dining room. The ceilings of both the ground and upper floors were of solid oak, and one of the bedrooms, on the first floor, was 18ft. in length, and was a sitting room. The windows were fitted with wooden shutters, which could be closed securely at night.
"The building was erected in a time when building material was not plentiful, and had to be transported great distances, the timber coming from the banks of the Tamar River.
"There was also a kitchen built at the same time, and in the garden there were two large sheds built.
"This old house is very similar to the old Georgian mansions which are to be seen in England.
"One can imagine the great changes which have occurred in this old home since 1738, the family having had four different owners. In 1855, the house was re-built by Mr. G. Everett, a builder, and in 1902, the roof was changed from slate to iron. The house was last occupied by Mrs. M. Everett.
"The old house is now in a very ruinous condition, and was at one time used as a dwelling for unmarried girls, one of whom, however, was married, and the building has now been closed by the owner

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

ocr.sentence: "EMBALMING MISERY" ' Mr. Churchill said that Parliament resolved to set the nation free would soon enable Britain to earn its own living in the world. On the other hand, he said, the Socialist policy of equalising. misery and organising scarcity, instead of allowing diligence self-reliance, and ingenuity to produce abundance, had only to he prolonged to be fatal to Britain. "The process of establishing the Socialist State has only begun," Mr. Churchill warned. He said that the Socialist Government spent in its term of office more than £17,000 million sterling, including enormous sums given or loaned from abroad. They had exacted the heaviest taxation in the world, It was now £500 million more even than in the height of the war. The value of the British pound had fallen since the war by not less than 44d. "This has struck a heavy blow at social services. Socialist claims about safeguarding or extending social services are vitiated by the fraud of giving only 16/4 and calling it £1. "This is one of the gravest evils which we have to face and remember, we still have the consequences of devaluation coming upon us to make it worse." "TERRIBLE AWAKENING" Mr. Churchill warned Britons that, if they shrugged their shoulders at the perils of the future, a terrible awakening lay not so far ahead. Class quarrels and endless party strife on the background of apathy, indifference, and be- wilderment will lead us all to ruin, he said. Mr. Churchill said that, once the basic standard of life and labour was secured, the Con , servatives would provide free A opportunities to rise. "Everyone will be allowed to make the best of himself," he said ' "There still remain forces in our island that can bring all our ' true glories back, and lift our people once again to the van ' guard of Christian civilisation," ' said Mr. Churchill.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

MALTA, Aug 23 (A.A.P.) All defences at Malta have been manned. The Territorials and auxiliary units have responded magnificently to the recruiting call. Gas masks are being distributed. An Italian who was alleged to be photographing the shore defences has been arrested.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

K.C. is to be elevated to the Bench of the Supreme Court of New South Wales as a Justice of the Peace. There are at least two reasons why the K.C. should not be called upon to perform any- functions as Judge Clive: (1) A Justitio has never been known to "carry on." (2) Any honest man holding the position of Justitio should have made better use of his classical education at Sydney University. There are, of course, dozens of competent lawyers in New South Wales who should be given g Wnl when in such circumstances the bench beckets them. Why not, for instance, call on Mr. Reginald Sleep or Mr. Arnold Withy? There is, of course, something about a crown of another that goes to one's head as well as to one's pocket. But the right preparation for any task at the front-line of the Bench, including an appointment as Judge Clive, consists of getting some wartime training with the arms of the battlefield. If you hope to be 'rewarded] with a Justice of the Peace Judgeship in the Army, you begin your career as a barrister where some others begin theirs: in the trenches. In this way we learn the value of practice in Court; and we learn to value it considerably more. Would Mr. Evatt: become a valuable instrument 'in the prosecution of our civil izers ,he practises with some of the less brutal means of inducing a man to take action voluntarily? If Mr. Evatt is convinced that this disorder is "a little thing" for an old B.A. to take it on, why not advise on such matters as he values defending Const. Farrer Crabtree? ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

"The Pageant of Nations," which was presented at the Sydney Town Hall last night and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and elaborately produced entertainments ever seen in Australia. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council in collaboration with the Consular Corps. Ireland and Scotland take the stage.

ocr.region: Magistrate Bars Mr. Evatt 1 Mr Beavers, S.M., yesterday refused to allow the Chief Secretary (Mr. Clive Evatt) to be represented at Central Court during the hearing of the Sunday films case. Mr. Alan Bagot asked Mr. Beavers for permission to intervene on behalf of the Chief Secretary's Department He said the whole question hinged on the discretion of the Minister. _ Yesterday William Frederick Farrer Crabtree, private secretary to Mr. Evatt, produced documents which had been subpoenaed at an earlier hearing but not produced. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. NEW SUMMONSES The two men are accused of contravening Section 19 of the N.S.W. Theatres and Public Halls Act by screening films at the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. He is responsible to the Crown and Parliament. "It is not for the Court to interfere. "The Minister is in a most unusual position under the Act. He has the sole right to say whether a theatre or a public house is in fact a theatre or a public house. The hearing was further adjourned to November 2. Mr. J. W. Smythe (by Bartier and Purcell) for Harrop; Mr. W. J. Bradley. K.C., and Mr. H. Maguire. K.C. (by Murphy and Moloney), for Cook; Mr. C. Begg (by Whitehead and Ferranti) for Scheinwald.

In our view of what the pageant is supposed to represent, we have no doubt that there is no more impressive spectacle to be had on Australian land than the magnificent National Council, in this town. A monument which, as the most extensive of the national celebrations, will be the centre of a new national debate and perhaps of the new nation - the National Council of Australia - may well have a more important function than we think it can. The Council has been erected by Mr. T. A. Taylor, of St. George in Melbourne. There is a monument in a stone, on which stands an effigy of a great Grand Master whose birth was known as 'The Big Indian.' This monument was erected by a British officer of the Royal Navy in 1846. The great Grandmaster was the Duke of Wellington, and he was one of the first to arrive at New Zealand, after his return from the war with the Japanese. He went ashore with Captain T. J. Collins, who, being stationed in South Africa, gave a brief address as to the Indian tribes and the Great Barrier Reef. In another speech he referred to the great Indian nation and said: "I have a great deal to say about the present national events. But I have a word of caution about the subject. This is not an election, but a solemn and solemn affair, a solemn and solemn occasion. The great national events in this country are not to be left to the people of the country, but rather to the people of the world. They are not to be left to those who are ignorant of the history of our continent. The history of our country and of the world is far greater than that which we are accustomed to believe. The national national events must be, first, solemn and solemn, and, second, to the people of the nation. This is not to diminish the importance of these national events in our country or in that of the nations of the world. The National Council of Australia is a great memorial to our country, and it is no longer necessary to pay tribute to it in the name of those who are the founders of it. In the national interest, the National Council has always been an organ of good government. This National Council has always been, in the national interest, an institution for the promotion of good government. It has always been an institution of good government. The only political organization which we possess in the country and which has been the foundation of our government for half a century, is the National Council

Theatre, which has had a great success in Australia, is experiencing some difficulties, among which are the demand of the business community to give up the works of Shakespeare, and the difficulties arising from the increasing popularity of other plays. The demand for these plays has, perhaps, been the most important source of tension between the directors and the theatre owners.

It has been stated that the Government does not have the power to prohibit theatricals from being screened in Sydney but that it is possible to bring the law into force in certain instances, when there is a case of an unfair prosecution. In recent years, however, the laws of the land have been the subject of a number of prosecutions. This time the charges are of a very severe nature. They relate to the practice of screening the theatricals for the King's Cross Theatrette.

Mr. Harrop was charged with three offences:

First, he was charged with screening the Sydney's theatricals for the King's Cross Theatrette on Sunday, August 12, 1908, when he was an Assistant General Manager of the S.A.M.F. in Sydney. The offence took place at the Theatre Royal, King's Cross, between May and September 1912, when Mr. Harrop was Director of the S.A.M.F. in Sydney. The offences were, among other things, screening the Sydney's theatricals in the King's Cross Theatrette at the Theatre Royal. The King's Cross Theatrette was located at the top of Theatret.

Second, he was charged with screening the Sydney's theatricals at the Theatre Royal, King's Cross, on Sunday, August 12, 1908, when he was Director of the S.A.M.F. in Sydney. The offence took place in the Theatre Royal, King's Cross, between January and May 1912, when Mr. Harrop was Director of the S.A.M.F. In those years Mr. Harrop was an Assistant General Manager of the S.A.M.F. In those years, it is said, he screened the Sydney's theatricals for the Theatre Royal and the Theatre Royal Cinema.

ocr.region: PAGEANT OF NATIONS." GREAT SPECTACLE. Magnificent Scenes. The Pageant of Nations," which was presented in the Sydney Town Hall last night, and will be staged every night this week as part of the Anniversary celebrations, is one of the most spectacular and. elaborately - produced en- tertainments ever seen in Australia. Full of glittering colour, the pageant is something of a feast both for the eye and the car, in its brilliant national settings, ensembles, and dances, and in its sparkling music. Tile crowded hall was almost transformed, with the organ blotted out, a vast gold pillared stage and centre platform built specially for the occasion, and more than 2000 men, women and children in a blaze of spotlights for a score or more of lavish scenes. The pageant was written and produced by Mr. J. J. Collins for the Celebrations Council, in collaboration with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. JOHN BULL'S CONGRATULATIONS. The brilliant scene opened with a prelude in which partly John Bull (Mr. Claude Flem- ing), grasping the hand of young Australia (Master Ronald Rouscl), briefly addressed the audience and expressed the pride with which they were celebrating the 150th birthday of one of their sturdiest sons." The strikingly impressive Empire pageant, constituting the first part of the programme and followed by the pageant and parade of the nations, Is headed by England, symbolised by an old English inn in the background; the Sydney Folk Song Choir, as huntsmen in rollicking hunting songs, and by a ballet of young women, also In hunting costume. The scene shifts to India, with lavishly-costumpd girls, traders, beggars, and tourists In a bazaar. With his entourage in glittering robes and turbans, an Indian prince makes a majestic entry. Canada next comes into the sparkling picture. Members of the Langlea Operatic Society, in the uniforms of the Canadian Royal North-west Mounted Police, sing a spirited chorus as they march down the centre platform and join Totem Pole girls and Red Indians, and Rose Marie (Miss Gwladys Evans). IRELAND AND WALES. Ireland is next brilliantly portrayed, in an enchanting assemblage of colleen and harpists, the scene closing with a joyous Irish jig. Then comes Wales, with men and women in picturesque national costumes, and folk songs by the Sydney Folk Song Choir. There is another storm of applause as a sturdy Maori chieftain conveys the greetings of New Zealand and Samoa, and is followed by Maori men and girls, in posture dances and other movements. Following New Zealand comes South Africa. Through a huge portrait of Cecil Rhodes is seen family, first, a university quadrangle, symbolising Rhodes's great work in the cause of education, and then a diamond mine. Miss South Africa closes a brilliant scene as she moves up the steps and unfolds a vast black train, shimmering with diamonds. Scotland next comes into the scene with the merry skirt of pipes, the joyous swing of kilts and spirited Scottish dancing and marching. EMPIRE PARADE. Even more spectacular and impressive is the closing Empire parade, in which 25 or more countries are represented, in period settings and traditional costumes, and headed by standard-bearers. The last to make it entry is Australia, symbolised strikingly by picturesquely-costumed characters, represent- ing gum nuts, koalas, waratah, wattles, and flannel flowers. Following Australia, and closing the stately procession, is Britannia. The vast stage is a blaze of colour as Britannia takes the centre of it, and is joined by Young Australia on her right and John Bull on her left to the inspiring and stirring notes of "Land of Hope r^d Glory." PARADE OF NATIONS. The nations of the world are represented in magnificent scenes featuring their national music and dances. With the whole of them finally grouped, the curtains rise to reveal also the British Empire. On the entry of Young Australia, there is a burst of joyous music and white doves soaring above as the figure of Peace appears. The choir, conducted by Mr. Horace Keats, also plays a distinctive part in the pageant.

The entire programme, including all the programmes in the main, is drawn up and submitted to the Council by Mr. F. S. Gower, the Consul, at the request of the Crown. For a short time there will be a short public presentation of the pageant. The next performance will be celebrated with a performance of the Sydney Opera House orchestra, and will be at 10.30 p.m. on the following evening. A special evening of dance is being given by a young Melbourne dance troupe. It consists of the Royal Society of Dance, and with them the Melbourne City Arts Council, and the Royal Melbourne Art Gallery, in a concert, "The Best of the Dance." There will be no tickets for public performances. This program is produced by Mr. C. D. Catt, Director of the Sydney Opera House, and Mr. S. G. Paley, Director of the Victoria University, and in association with the Australian Opera Company. All the programmes will be presented in an orchestra arrangement with a chorus and orchestra. The program will be presented at the Sydney Opera House, in a number of pieces of music in the operatic style, and some of the best known works will be performed. The Opera House and Melbourne Opera House will each offer their own show. Tickets are also available for private performances at both places. The first concert will be held at 2.30 p.m. on Friday, November 18, at the Victoria Hall. A second concert, "The Greatest Musical Festival Ever," will take place at 5.30 p.m. on Saturday, November 19, at the Victoria Hall, and a third at 7.30 p.m. on Sunday, November 20, at the Victoria Hall. The concert and parade are the most elaborate events ever offered by a public organist, and the whole of it is the finest of all that has ever been performed on Australian soil. For further information about these performances, contact the Consul's office on 956-5444.

It was written about three years ago, and the story is one of the most interesting in Australia, that the Great War has had a powerful influence on the history of our country. And now it is being told in the greatest, and most important way possible. For this is the first volume of a series which will be published in our journal over the next few weeks. It is the work of an eminent Australian poet and poetical critic, and one of the finest works of the period.

THE GREAT WAR OF 1812, by A. S. GOWER. In the midst of the excitement of the Great War, and the prospect of a great victory, there is now a remarkable piece of writing and writing which has made such a sensation in our society. It is not the first of its kind, but it has been written in a remarkable and striking manner. It is a work of a character and character that is as close to history as ever has been written.

THE GREAT WAR OF 1812, by A. S. GOWER. When I first heard of this work, it was not thought that such a work would be made, and I was not prepared to accept the terms of the deal I had signed. I had a great feeling of dismay, which was not of this time of year, for in the late summer of 1812 I had received a letter from a certain lady, who had gone to London and been in conversation with the chief officer of our country, General Grant. As it was the first time that I had ever received such a news, I was greatly shocked. What sort of thing was the matter? It had been a long time since I had heard a speech that was so bold, such as this one, or that of the General. I should have thought it was as serious, if not more so, than the other, had not my conscience been clear. I had never heard a word of it from any official, and so I felt that there was something very special going on. The lady, who had written to me, said that the author, had left an impression of what she had heard, which made her very anxious for some time. She did not know what she should do; the writer did not know how to act in the face of such a situation. She did not know what to say. When I looked at her face, I found it so earnest and true that I could not help thinking of it in the face of such a situation, I asked her if she knew anything about the story. She did not, and so I had the courage to write it down. I will not attempt to describe it

Transcript NEW ZEALAND. Tuesday, October 14, 1924. PAGE 7 SUNDAY'S CROWD. 25,000 See the Pageant. CROWD FOR SATURDAY AND SUNDAY. Increasing Audience Numbers Each Night. With the completion of the second performance of the Pageant of Nations last night, the crowds which have thronged the Sydney Town Hall during the first three nights of the en- tertainment can be calculated. It is estimated that at least 25,000 people have seen the pageant. The crowds have been steadily increasing during the past three nights. On Saturday about 1000 tickets wereaniu, and on Sunday 2000 more were sold. In the Sydney Town Hall the audience is seated on three sides and in tiers of stairs. The centre platform is reserved for the stage. Last night the first two sections of the audience were nearly filled and theальtter rows were quite crowded. There was still a considerable amount of vacant room on the side balconies. It was said that about 1000 seats were reserved for special guests last night. The attendance last night was the largest that had ever been seen in the Town Hall. The total crowd for the three performances last night was estimated at 8000, a substantial increase over the previous night. AUDIENCE ACCLAIM. The audience at the final performance of the Pageant of Nations last night gave a resounding encore for the British anthem, "God Save the King." During the anthem the audience clapped and sang in great measure. During the curtain call the audience gave its unmistakable applause when the pageant was first announced and when Miss Gwladys Evans first appeared as Rose Marie. The crowd went wild when the curtain was raised. The performance last night was one of the best, and the crowd gave its enthusiastic approval by rising in mass as the curtain fell. It is understood that a large proportion of those who attended last night were from inter-state and overseas. It is stated that a special train has been run by the Government from Grafton to Sydney for the purpose of carrying people to the pageant. AUSTRALIA. A large proportion of the Australians who saw the Pageant of Nations last night were Sydney residents. The great attendance last night was the largest seen at the Sydney Town Hall for a long time. The crowd was largely composed of school children, and they gave great evidence of enjoyment and enthusiasm. There were a great many women and children present, and they gave much applause to Miss Evans and the other dancers. The performance last night was one of the best, and the audience went wild when the curtain was raised and Miss Evans first appeared as Rose Marie. After the show there were large crowds in Pitt and Hunter streets and in nearby thorough- fares. There were no incidents of a disturbanctive character. It is said that the Government will reimburse the City Council for the expenses incurred in holding the pageant. TRADE MEETS. The hearing was adjourned to enable the Chief Secretary to produce the documents. Before the Court were Kenneth Frank Easton Cook, of the King's Cross Theatrette, and Natan Scheinwald.i of Spring Street, Sydney, They are being prosecuted at the instance of William Robert Harrop, secretary of the N.S.W. branch of the Australian Theatrical and Amusements Association. The prosecutions were laid under the Theatres and Public Halls Act, 1908-46. . Mr. Harrop is also honorary business manager of the Motion Picture Exhibitors Association. August 12 for which an admission charge was made. "-Further summonses have been laid against Hilda Blanche Hattam, the Australian Biograph Company Pty [Ltd.. and the Premier Theatre (Surry Hills) Pty. Ltd. for screening films on Sunday. August 19. r Asking for leave to appear for Mr. Evatt, Mr. Bagot said yesterday that the Minister, in his discretion, had approved the Sunday screenings and it was not a matter for the Court to grant such approval. It was up to the Minister, who could regulate or prohibit the conduct of any Sunday entertainment if, in his opinion, it offended against good behaviour. MINISTER'S RIGHT Mr. C. Begg (for Schein- wald) said Mr. Harrop was asking the Court to sit in judgment on a Minister of the Crown. He said: "The Minister is not responsible to this Court. For the last time in Australia's history, a pageant of nations will be staged." This is a remarkable day for our civilisation," said Dr. James Wilson, a writer in the Sydney paper, which appeared in the late days of January. The pageant was produced by Mr. J. J. Collins, for the Celebrations Council, in association with the Consular Corps. It was attended by the Governor and Lady Wakehurst, the Chief Justice, Sir Frederick Jordan, and Lady Jordan, the Premier and Mrs. Stevens, the Minister in Charge of the Celebrations, Mr. Dlinnlnghnm, and Mrs. Dunningham, and other representative citizens. The band was in attendance, with the chorus, the drum and harp, and the choir choir, in their entirety, all of the members of the Queen's Legion. Dynatoma is an antilope, the largest mammal in the genus (5 meters in size). They feed on carnivorous birds and animals, but are particularly active in winter, when they use their long, sharp tongues to scrape the underside of their tails to collect dung from animals and to burrow their holes. When they get drunk, the animals usually suck their own urine as well as the dung from the antilope's body, so that the antilope becomes much more aggressive.
Dynatoma appears to be very vocal. They can often be heard for more than 2 hours in the morning, during their nocturnal activities. When they come out of their sleep, the loud snaring sound of their tails has been heard by people living in the wild.

ocr.sentence: παυλοσλεγων χε ημας εξηγορασεν εκτης καταρας τοῦ νομου γενομενος υπερημῶν κα ταρα ειτοινην αυτοςθες ων ι της ουσιας εκει ης της απορρη του τυγχανων δια φιλανιαν αφατον ταυτα απαντα κατεδεξατο διημας την σφιαν την ημετεραν τι ουκαν ειημεναυ τοι δικαι ονπεριτους ομογενεις επιδειξασθαι ταμελητα ημετερα ωστεκαι της φαρυγγος αυτος εξαρ πασαι του διαβόλου και προς την της αρετης όδινχειραγωμισαι όσω γαρψυχι εωματος κρειτγων τοσουτον των χρημασιβοη θουντων τοις δεομενοις ουτωμει ναναφι οανται των αμοιμων οιδια της παρινεσε ωσκαι της συνεχους διδασκαλιας τους βα θυθφυς και αναπεπτωκοτας εν αγοντες επι τηνευθειαν όδον και δειηναντες της μενκα κιας τοδυσοδες τησδεκαταθναρετης την πολλην ευμορφιαν ταυτα τοῖνην απαντα ιδοτες προτων αλλων απαντων των κιω τι κῶν περιτης κατα ψυχην σριας διαλεγομε θα τοις πλησιον εις ταυτην αυτοὺς εναγιντες την μεριμναν αγαπητον γαρ αγαπητον συ εχως ταυτα ενηχουμενην ψυχην δυν ηθη αι ανεν εγκειν εκτης αλω σσου των κακων των εντωμεσωστρεφομενων και περιγενεσθαι της των παθων επαναστασεος απερδι ην εκως πολιορκειτην ημετεραν ψυχην οῳδια τουτοχρεία κμειν πολλης της αγρυπνιας επειδη και διην εκης ημιν εστιν οπολεμοσς

ocr.sentence: παυλοσλεγων χε ημας εξηγορασεν εκτης καταρας τοῦ νομου γενομενος υπερημῶν κα ταρα ειτοινην αυτοςθες ων ι της ουσιας εκει ης της απορρη του τυγχανων δια φιλανιαν αφατον ταυτα απαντα κατεδεξατο διημας την σφιαν την ημετεραν τι ουκαν ειημεναυ τοι δικαι ονπεριτους ομογενεις επιδειξασθαι ταμελητα ημετερα ωστεκαι της φαρυγγος αυτος εξαρ πασαι του διαβόλου και προς την της αρετης όδινχειραγωμισαι όσω γαρψυχι εωματος κρειτγων τοσουτον των χρημασιβοη θουντων τοις δεομενοις ουτωμει ναναφι οανται των αμοιμων οιδια της παρινεσε ωσκαι της συνεχους διδασκαλιας τους βα θυθφυς και αναπεπτωκοτας εν αγοντες επι τηνευθειαν όδον και δειηναντες της μενκα κιας τοδυσοδες τησδεκαταθναρετης την πολλην ευμορφιαν ταυτα τοῖνην απαντα ιδοτες προτων αλλων απαντων των κιω τι κῶν περιτης κατα ψυχην σριας διαλεγομε θα τοις πλησιον εις ταυτην αυτοὺς εναγιντες την μεριμναν αγαπητον γαρ αγαπητον συ εχως ταυτα ενηχουμενην ψυχην δυν ηθη αι ανεν εγκειν εκτης αλω σσου των κακων των εντωμεσωστρεφομενων και περιγενεσθαι της των παθων επαναστασεος απερδι ην εκως πολιορκειτην ημετεραν ψυχην οῳδια τουτοχρεία κμειν πολλης της αγρυπνιας επειδη και διην εκης ημιν εστιν οπολεμοσς
groundtruth.sentence: παυλος λεγων Χς ἡμᾶς ἐξηγόρασεν ἐκ τῆς κατάρας τοῦ νόμου γενόμενος ὑπὲρ ἡμῶν κα τάρα ει τοινυν αυτος θς ων κ της ουσιας εκει νης της απορρητου τυγχανων δια φιλανιαν αφατον ταυτα απαντα κατεδεξατο δι ημας κ την σριαν την ημετεραν τι ουκ αν ειημεν αυ τοι δικαιον περι τους ομογενεις επιδειξασασθαι κ τα μιλητα ημετερα ωστε και της φαρυγγος αυτους εξαρπασαι του διαβολου και προς την της αρετης οδον χειραγωγησαι οσω γαρ ψυχη σωματος κρειττων τοσουτον των χρημασι βοη θουντων τοις δεομενοις ουτω μειζονων αξι ουνται των αμοιβων οι δια της παραινεσε ως και της συνεχους διδασκαλιας τους ρα θυμους κ αναπεπτωκοτας εναγοντες επι την ευθειαν οδον κ δεικνυντες της μεν κα κιας το δυσειδες της δε κατα θν αρετην την πολλην ευμορφιαν ταυτα τοινυν απαντα ειδοτες προ των αλλων απαντων των βιωτι κων περι της κατα ψυχην σριας διαλεγομε θα τοις πλησιον εις ταυτην αυτους εναγοντες την μεριμναν αγαπητον γαρ αγαπητον συ νεχως ταυτα ενηχουμενην ψυχην δυνηθη ναι ανενεγκειν εκ της αβυσσου των κακων των εν τω μεσω στρεφομενων και περιγενεσθαι της των παθων επαναστασεως απερ δι ηνεκως πολιορκει την ημετεραν ψυχην κ δια τουτο χρεια ημιν πολλης της αγρυπνιας επειδη και διηνεκης ημιν εστιν ο πολεμος

Petrarch: It should be pointed out that what is said of the Old Testament is not a matter of faith, but a matter of general applicability: namely, that the meaning of the verse is that we ought to remember it and to take our own course in the interpretation. This passage is particularly relevant as we deal with the following issues:

[B]aric and Phoccyra [the patriarchs of the same church, having received some of the sons of the Romans, having risen before them] say, 'Thou shalt be a priest among the Jews. Thou shalt do the will of Christ.' When this statement is read from the same point, the first question is answered; and then the second question is asked.
